        "description": {
            "name": "description",
            "type": "java.lang.String",
            "value": "Hello,\r\n\r\nI ran into an issue with verifying whether a submit button was clicked or not.\r\nFirst of all, here is how I create the form in the form class's init() method:\r\n{code:title=Form.php|borderStyle=solid}\r\n$element = new Zend_Form_Element_Submit('DOWNLOAD_ARCHIVE');\r\n...\r\n...\r\n$this->addElement($element);\r\n{code}\r\n\r\nI then create an object of the form in my controller:\r\n\r\n{code:title=Controller.php|borderStyle=solid}\r\n$form = new App_Form();\r\nif ($form->getElement('DOWNLOAD_ARCHIVE')->isChecked()) {\r\n    \/\/do some stuff if submit was clicked\r\n}\r\n{code}\r\n\r\nThe isChecked() method doesn't work out correctly because I am using Zend_Translate to translate the value of my submit buttons.\r\nFor example, the \"DOWNLOAD_ARCHIVE\" element name(= the displayed text on a button) gets translated to \"Download archive\" or \"Archiv herunterladen\" .\r\nProblem now is, that the isChecked() method looks into the request if the value of the button was submitted. \r\nIn my case, it looks whether \"DOWNLOAD_ARCHIVE\" is part of the request array or not. But it is never, because the array value of \"DOWNLOAD_ARCHIVE\" is never \"DOWNLOAD_ARCHIVE\" but either \"Download archive\" or \"Archiv herunterladen\" .\r\n\r\nI solved this by not using the isChecked() method but like this:\r\n{code:title=Controller.php|borderStyle=solid}\r\nif ($this->_request->getParam('DOWNLOAD_ARCHIVE', null) !== null) {\r\n    \/\/do some stuff if submit was clicked\r\n}\r\n{code}\r\n\r\nUnfortunately that would make the isChecked() method unneccessary.\r\nI hope this is an actual error and not simply a wrong use of the components by me.\r\nIf you need any further information, feel free to ask.\r\n"
        },
